anuhe: caterpillar of the convolvulus hawk-moth (Agrius convolvuli)
ariki: paramount chief of a tribe, the most senior by descent of the rangatira (chiefs) of the tribe
hongi: The Maori greeting of touching noses.
kauri: A conifer of the genus Agathis, family Araucariaceae, found in Australasia and Melanesia.
koria: Korea (a geographic region consisting of two countries in East Asia, commonly known as South Korea and North Korea; formerly a single country)
kātoa: Any of the red variety of Leptospermum scoparium, a shrub or small tree native to New Zealand and southeast Australia.
kōhia: Passiflora tetrandra, a kind of passionfruit endemic to New Zealand.
kōhua: boiler, pot (any metal cooking vessel for boiling food)
marae: The courtyard of a wharenui or meeting-house and the buildings around it.
ngaro: blowfly, in connection with mākutu the fly represented the life or spirit of the person involved.
ngāti: Prefix for an iwi or hapū; tribal group.
riaki: to lift up or raise, to elevate
rāhui: restriction of access to a place (as a form of taboo)
rākau: A weapon; a club or bat.
rātou: they, them (plural; three or more people)
taupō: Taupo (a town in Waikato, New Zealand, on the shore of the lake)
tawau: latex or milky sap of any plant.
tinei: to extinguish, to put out (of a fire, light)
toroa: an albatross, especially the royal albatross or wandering albatross
tārua: to double something, to copy, to duplicate
tēnei: this (referring to something near to the speaker)
whara: Any of the several plants in the families Asteliaceae and Xanthorrhoeaceae.
wātea: to be free, unoccupied, vacant, open, blank, available, clear, unencumbered.
āpuru: to suppress, shut up, crowd together, overwhelm.
āwhio: to go in circles or in a roundabout way, to snake
